title: Net or tarp attachment hook for the Better Shelter residence

description.text:
This is a hook that can be fitted on the screws that are used to construct a Better Shelter (by IKEA foundation) Refugee Housing Unit (RHU). It was designed by the participants of the Core Relief (www.corerelief.org) workshop.
The hook is used to allow the visitors of the hospitality camps to attach nets and tarps to create shade without damaging the RHU or creating a fire hazard.

This design is a proposal for an extra standardized item that can be manufactured alongside the other parts of the RHU. It also includes a proposal for a urban plan (different layouts.max) of the camp that will maximize the comfort level in terms of shading and minimize fire hazard with the planned placement of shading, thanks to the hooks. The design is not "finished" but is something that can be improved to become a mass manufactured item.

sanding away support

Support was added in the model in order to be able to print it well and not depend on the printer or slicer's support functions.

space for rings of taurpaulin

The hook is dimensioned to be able to fit the rings that are pressed into tarpaulin sheets.
Another closed design is also made to fit the nets.

description.text:
I ride a motorcycle, and as fellow motorcyclist will know, wind noise reaches hearing damaging levels. Many wear foam earplugs but this blocks out too much, I noticed that earbuds, block the wind but let most other things through almost unhindered, like car horns. Wearing earbuds is illegal, wearing earplugs is not, having a helmet audio system is not. So after installing a helmet intercom/audio system, I wanted the protection of earbuds without the cord.
I came up with these, they accept skull candy, and probably many other tips from earbuds.

They work quite well as Is although I was thinking about a tube down the middle and some sort of stuffing in the larger bulb section like cotton or something. To let higher frequency through but not the roar of the wind.

EDIT, I have been using these a while now and they work better than expected as is, the round part could probably be shorter to make taking helmet on and off easier, but they block almost all wind but let the helmet system through just fine. When going slow in town it makes the helmet system quieter, but I can hear gps directions and song directions at highway speeds with these in, I couldn't understand vocals before without them.

title: Flexible Jerrycan (jerrysack) adapters for resuscitator or water filter

description.text:
These are adapters that can be printed to add extra functionality to the flexible jerrycan (jerrysack) which is part of the Core Relief item catalogue of the UNHCR. They were designed by the participants of the Core Relief (www.corerelief.org) workshop.

It contains

  • a cap adapter to attach a regular sized PET bottle cap
    This adapter is useful to limit the flow of water and dispense it more easily. Some PET bottle caps, like those of sports drinks, even have a special dispenser that you can now also use on the jerrysack.
  • a water filter, adapted from the design of http://www.instructables.com/id/Open-Source-3D-Printed-Water-Filter/
    This filter needs activated charcoal to work. See the instructable for extra information.
  • and an adapter for a breathing mask
    This will not necessarily work for all breathing mask. Only the one we tried out. Because the jerrycan is flexible it can be used to push air into the mask.

These designs are not "finished" but are something that can be improved upon and be an inspiration for others that are attempting similar endeavors.
Depending on the types of emergency scenarios one is looking at, the 3d printer can be useful to get these specific tools on the field as quick as possible. Or if for example, clean water is high in demand, the water filters could be mass produced as a cheaper alternative or extra solution to supplying bottled water.
This is how to use the jerrysack as a breather device.

title: Generic E3D v5 clone / Metal Extruder Mount Assembly

description.text:
Update 13.06.2017 corrected the title its e3d v5 not mk5 - sheesh

My Version of a modular full replacement for the problematic x-carriage mount assembly my CTC printer came with. It mounts a cheap E3D clone hotend to a common metal mk8 sized extruder.

The base design comes with a place to attach a 8mm distance induction sensor but no fan ducting since I use large Fans mounted to the frame of my printer to good effect, but I might do a version of the "Front" with an airflow redirect in the future.

The mount is split into 3 parts for easier printing if you rotate them correctly. The parts are joined by M3 screws of various lengths and an optional very long M3 screw or 3mm rod for extra horizontal stiffness.

The attachment holes to the x-carriage are spaced 30mm for 2 M3 screws but I made a more standard 23mm spaced version of the base with 4 M4 holes you can alternatively print. If your hotend nozzle ends up being too low then there is another alternative with an additional 2mm of headroom. The stepper motor meant to be used with this should be 39mm deep and will fit Quite snugly. The fan should be a 40x40x10 fan.

This is the function used to generate the space for the E3D clone hotend radiator in case you want to check if yours fit: 

module hotend(){
    e3d=[[9.4,50,0],
    [16.9,4,23.1],
    [12.9,5.7,18.6],
    [16.9,3.8,14.2],
    [16.9,2,9.9],[25.5,32,-9.1]];
    for(c=e3d){
       translate([0,0,c[2]])cylinder(d=c[0],h=c[1],center=true,$fn=76);
    }
}

I printed and tested all the parts on my 3d printer. In fact my printer prints using this right now. :)

There is a more elaborate explanation of how I put this together in a blog on my website here: http://watersideworkshop.com/2016/11/06/i-want-to-be-ironman-for-halloween/

When I make a costume, I try to make it functional, cool looking, but also warm so when we are finished, he doesn’t have to hide it with a jacket. All the pieces were printed out and sewn onto a red hoodie one size bigger than he is for the room needed to sew on pieces and hide wires, but also so I can layer warm clothes underneath.

Some of these pieces were heated with a heat gun (hair dryer works) and bent to shape. They were also quickly airbrushed and hand painted with Auto-air paint. It was a fun project that we enjoyed doing.

Safety disclaimer: This costume could be harmful to wear in a car or vehicle due to the stiffness of the plastic with belts, but it easily allows enough movement to take on and off for a car seat.

This is a custom print cooling solution for the Craftbot, replacing the stock solution.

Introduction

The stock cooling on the Craftbot doesn't really cool well enough right where it is needed. Instead it provides a general flow of air from two angled axial fans, blowing in the direction of the heater block and nozzle.

The big problem with creating a custom solution is that there is very little useable space around the extruder when it approaches the x and y limits. The Craftbot is a very compact machine, and while that is very nice for your desktop space, it makes life hard for someone trying to create a custom cooler.

This cooler uses a common 5015 blower fan that pressurizes a plenum chamber, from which three nozzles direct the air just where it is needed, close to the nozzle. The flow from the three nozzles is fairly even, providing good cooling from three directions.

I have only tested this on my Craftbot 2, but I believe that the Craftbot Plus should be identical. I do not know if it will also fit the original Craftbot.

Printing

The cooling duct needs to be printed on it's back, and some supports are needed:

1) Inside the cavity, just where the middle nozzle is
2) In the opening for the blower fan, to make sure it doesn't droop
3) Under the two side nozzles
4) Under the vertical walls
5) Where the blower fan screw mount is (can often be skipped, though)

Do not go overboard with supports, as it will only make removal difficult.

Recommended resolution is 0.2 mm, and it is probably best to use a material which handles the heat (ABS/PETG), as this sits very close to the heater block.

The mounting bracket and the connector holder bracket does not need supports, but it may be necessary to clean up the holes a little bit.

There are some very thin walls in the duct (0.8 mm), but when assembled, it will be plenty strong enough.

Recommended supports for printing Assembling and additional hardware

To assemble this, you will need:

  1. A 5015 blower fan (like this one: http://www.ebay.com/itm/222278030829), needs to draw less than 0.24 A, but for good efficiency it should be 0.14 A or more.
  2. A 40 x 10 mm axial fan (can re-use one of the original fans if needed). If buying a new fan, make sure it has a similar rating to the stock one (0.12 A).
  3. M3 socket head screws:
    2 x 14 mm (for the extruder fan)
    1 x 20 mm (for the blower fan)
    2 x 20 mm (for mounting the bracket and the duct together)
    2 x 10 mm (for mounting the assembled cooler to the printer)
  4. One M2 15 mm socket head screw for the connector holder bracket

The holes has been sized so that the screw should thread right into the plastic, but I do recommend using a M3 tap to pre-cut the threads.

When assembling, first attach the top bracket to the duct itself, using two screws.

Then the blower fan should snap right into place, just insert it at an angle, and then rotate and push it into position before inserting the screw to hold it firmly in place. The little tab on the fan should lock into the slot in the cooling duct.

The extruder fan is screwed right onto the duct itself, using two screws.

I am not going into any details on the electrical part of this, but you will need to do some soldering to connect the fan wires to a suitable male connector to plug into the female connector on the Craftbot. Again, you can of course desolder this from the original cooling, but I'd recommend to keep that as-is, and just buy a new connector or use some pins soldered to the wire ends as a makeshift connector. However, be careful to insulate any bare wire, as short circuiting will blow the driver on the main board.

The assembled unit, ready to mount to the printer:

Assembled unit Notes

This cooler has been designed for the stock hotend, and will most likely not fit if you have a custom hotend on your machine.

And as mentioned, the space around the extruder is very sparse, and the clearances when using this cooler is extremely small. After mounting it, please move the extruder around manually to make sure it doesn't touch anything. Here are some images showing just how tight it is on my machine (a Craftbot 2).

Almost hitting the bolt heads for the Z-rods Barely any clearance to the right hand side frame lip

title: Adruino self-holding thick snap fitting bumper case. Easy first project for students and hobbyists

description.text:
Thicker version of Arduino Bumper with tabs and plastic front posts to securely hold your Arduino Uno board, while preventing shorts, desktop scratching, and clearing all pins.

Excellent first project for students and enthusiasts. Print your own Arduino bumper/mini-case

The walls are taller and the front port openings adjusted for a snug fit.

Simply tip your board and slide under the rear tabs and push into place.

Note: Rear tabs are self-supporting and get a little spaghetti under them. You can trim any big pieces with pointy scissors, but leave some under there to help friction fit the board and hold it into place.

One set of holes is left for rivets, screws, etc to permanently attach boards, but it does a good job of holding the board in the bumper on its own.

If you look into the grooves for the solder pins under the board on each side, you can see filament patterns to retain the "DIY 3D Printer look." Holding it up to the light reveals the inner structure as well.

Should work quite well in a classroom or other environment where boards are shuffled around. Works well with shields, too.

I've included the 123D Design file to allow easy customizing. STL and G-Code are also included. The G-Code is the slow setting for Monoprice IIIP (Wanhao i3 Select Plus), Ultimaker v2-ish printer.

If I print at REALLY FAST speed, it is still quite good, but you'll start to see tool lines and perhaps filament gaps. I was pushing my machine as a test.

Takes about 15-20 mins on fast (slice your own for your printer with your fast settings) or 30-60 mins on slow/best quality.

Bottom half of side walls should work well for raised lettering or customization. Slightly inset...watch for interference with other structures.

I used 1.75mm PLA from Hatchbox on the Monoprice IIIP Select Plus printer. 123D Design to import and remake the design, MeshMixer to make the STL, Cura III-P edition to slice.

Post up your makes!

Teachers, educators, hobbyists! If you use the ideas or files above to learn or teach someone else and found it useful, PLEASE provide some FEEDBACK ;)

If there is enough interest, I'll make more detailed lessons, complete with all files and information necessary for a successful learning experience.

Printer:

Monoprice IIIP (Wanhao/Ultimaker)

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.1mm

Notes:

Very tolerant of different print settings and speeds, layer thicknesses (I've tried 0.1 and 0.2) and run it wide open and still had usable- but noticeably different- results

Minor trimming

Minor trimming of stray strings, plus any large strings under the self-supporting tabs. Do NOT remove all of them, they help provide a good friction fit of the board.

Easily customizable first bumper for Arduino Uno boards. Good for experimenting with printer settings. Tolerant of extreme settings. Low risk of waste Students can resize, add text or other customizations to surface or bottom. Students can design and print rivets, plastic screws and nuts to secure if desired. Multiple colors or mixes or even materials can be used. By protecting the bottom pins, proper handling procedures and safety can be emphasized. 123D Design file included for simple tweaking. Excellent first design for students to immediately make something functional that allows full access to the Arduino board and all pins and connectors. Gives students investment/contribution to their electronics adventure. Relatively quick printing with good sized, thick base for bed adhesion, eliminating bad prints. Lots of extruder head movement is a good introduction to and demonstration of 3D printing, while entertaining to watch. Fill, layers, hollows, hanging filaments (easily trimmed) can demonstrate some of the limits of 3D printing.

Introduction to Rapid Prototyping using 3D Printing and Arduino Development Boards Students can start with the base 123D Design file and tweak the outer faces in a number of ways, including adding raised or recessed lettering or designs, adding mounts, feet, shaped pad, etc Model rotates nicely, has a lot of flat surfaces, recesses, angles, suspended tabs and is tight fitting. Some edges may have slight errors due to extra or thin filament, accuracy of machine, etc (ie front sockets under the USB and Power ports) that are easily explored and discussed, then trimmed with excellent results. Round mounting pins in the front set of board area are round and under close inspection demonstrate the limitations and challenges of printing layer-by-layer- rather than component at once. Cylinders built up one little layer at a time, then the extruder moving to other parts of the model before returning for the next layer reveal inaccuracies and limitations of consumer level 3D printing- which can be offered as a comparison to CNC cutting/milling/lathe machines or molded plastics. As your printing speeds approach 80mm/s, some anomalies will start to show, especially due to tool paths. Increasing the layer height from 0.1mm to 0.2mm will result in a fast print, but should trigger some warnings from your printer about being too fast for the filament, which could result in some slippage. Reducing your printing speed to 50 or so will allow you to print at this thicker layer. Printing at double the thickness, but slower can result in nearly the same print times, but may show more vertical banding than thinner layer settings. Experiment with different component print settings and speed (infill speed, inner face, outer face, movement speeds, filament retraction, extruder temperatures) Model is very simple to reliably reproduce without any manipulation. Using different colors or even customization can provide visual distinction between different students' projects and equipment. Sides can be extruded upwards (K command in 123D), then a top added and the model sliced by a plane to split into top and bottom halves of a case for more advanced modeling exercises. Note the difference in the plastic pin positions for a tight snap fit. Provides opportunity to discuss different techniques for form fitting plastic items. Example: If the pins were larger, they would fit tighter, but might not snap together due to print anomalies, or Arduino board production differences. Some slop is necessary, but offsetting slightly and using the flexible nature of the printed material allows minimal distortion without damage to the structure or the board, while still providing a tight, self-holding, snap-in fit. If using Cura or other slicing software, be sure to view the LAYERS view and allow students to drag the scroll bar to visually see and understand the various layers/slices that will produce the part, along with the blue tool paths. See if you can pick out the tool path that leads to a surface defect on only one side of the model! Combined with 123 Circuits (FREE!), this can be a good basic block for rapid prototyping, while demonstrating how various technologies can be combined as a rapid development environment in an educational, commercial, or home hobby environment. Good opportunity to discuss how technology allows prototyping and design for a minimal investment and footprint. Also shows how social media (thingiverse and others) allows sharing of ideas, products, and cooperative work models. Notice: Playing Air Hockey with Arduino boards snapped into these bumpers is NOT recommended.

Simplest material list ever!
  • Arduino Uno board
  • 3D printer with filament (PLA is very simple to use)
    • Optional:
  • 123D Design to manipulate model (FREE!)
  • Raspberry Pi 3 running octopi with tripod and webcam to live stream printer (offsite, from home, etc) Works well with computers and handheld devices (yes, phones)
  • MeshMixer (FREE!)
  • Cura (FREE!) or other slicer software.

Install software

  • Install 123D Design software and sign up for an account

  • Install MeshMixer (123D allows you to select the model and click an icon to send directly to MeshMixer. VERY simple)

  • Install slicing software. I used Cura/IIIP-version.

  • Have your 3D printer setup and SD Cards handy, or however you plan to deliver the files to your printer.

  • Have a couple of Arduino Uno boards handy.

  • Perhaps have an Arduino sketch, with arduino.cc installed and configured to upload to the boards.

  • Could have LED with resistors handy. After inserting the board into the bumper, have students plug LED + resistor into correct pins (match the sketch), plug into USB, open the sketch, upload and run it on the board, watch the LED blink.

This is a printable, sealed hourglass, that should print in one continuous part. The result should mystify and amaze. Or at least allow you to measure some period of time in a repeatable fashion.

Print in transparent PLA, with no support. Print about 75% of the part, but pause the printing before the top is sealed.
Pour in dry, clean, dark sand, until the bottom half of the hourglass is almost full. It may be easier to do this if your sand is in a paper tube or funnel, since the hourglass is fairly small.
Then resume printing, so that the hourglass is sealed. Flip it over, time how long it takes for the sand to make it through, and write that on the timer.
It's parametric, so you can modify variables to change the hourglass: Then generate a new hourglass and print it. Make it wide, skinny, tall, short, slow or fast. Have fun!

description.text:
It's a scale model (1/32) of a 4 truck, 8 axle flat car suited for 45mm tracks (Gauge I).
These cars are used in North America to move big and heavy loads. Having 8 axles on the car helps to spread the weight on the rails.
With the trucks mounted on rotating beams, this car can take very tight curves (tested on 600 mm radius curves).

0.1 and 0.2 mm

Notes:

Everything is printed in ABS using a 3D adhesive spray on a heated bed (100°). I find it easier to glue (with PVC glue).
You can also print it in PLA as most of the parts are screwed together. Small parts can be glued with super glue.

The central beam needs support to be printed so I've cut it in 2 to print it without support (the 2 parts are glued together).

You'll need to print four trucks : I've already published them on Thingiverse (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1803630) and have not included the files here..

The three parts of the flat bed can be glued (use small chunks of filament in the holes to align the parts) or bolted with 2 mm bolts and nuts (4 needed).

The Brake platform (03) is fixed with 3x8 mm screws as is the central beam (04) on the bed.
You'll have to glue the Brake Wheel Stand (09) and its various parts. Same goes for the grab irons and the ladders.

There's a spacer (06) you'll have to glue on the truck bolster. I's needed to adjust the height of the car.

I've designed a knuckle coupler with gearbox you can use for this car :http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1908821
